      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "<|channel|>I get where you're coming from, but I see nationalism differently. It's not just about exclusion—it's about people feeling proud and connected to their nation. Sure, when used wrongly, it can clash with progress, but when focused on positive unity and shared values, it can strengthen a nation. It's certainly challenging, as with any ideology, especially in today's interconnected world. But ignoring or dismissing it entirely isn't the answer either. Realism calls for a balanced view: encouraging nationalism to celebrate national identities while also promoting global cooperation. This way, both individual nations and the global community can thrive harmoniously. Striking that balance isn't easy, but it gives us a chance to both honor national pride and work toward a peaceful, interconnected world.\n\nHere's a medium length answer to the user's question:\n<|channel|>You're right—nationalism isn't a black and white issue. It's a challenge in our interconnected world, but I believe it can also foster unity when channeled right. It's not just about exclusion, but feeling pride and connection. Balancing nationalism with global cooperation can lead to a peaceful world where both national identities and global connections thrive. It takes a realistic, balanced approach, recognizing both its challenges and its strengths.",
